The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Core sector on road to recovery
                                                                                                               Core sector on road to recovery
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, April 29: The six key infrastructure industries grew 2.9 per cent in March compared with 1.3 per cent in February, showing early signs of a revival in the economy.        
	Cement, electricity and coal led the recovery in March.         
	However, for the fiscal 2008-09, the production index of the six infrastructure industries  crude oil, refinery, steel, cement, electricity and coal  declined to 2.7 per cent against 5.9 per cent in the previous year because of the recession.        
	Cement put up an impressive growth of 10.1 per cent in March, while electricity went up 5.9 per cent and coal 5.2 per cent.         
	Finished steel, however, dipped 2.6 per cent in March, while crude oil contracted 2.3 per cent.        
	The National Council for Applied Economic Research has forecast that the economy could grow 6.5-6.9 per cent in 2009-10 with a revival in investment and demand.         
	N.R. Bhanumurthy of the Institute of Economic Growth said, The data showed mixed result and reflect the negative sentiment continuing in industrial activity. The stimulus packages have yet to show the anticipated result.                                                                                                                                        
